metadata.name: M-tore #96
metadata.description: This token generates abstract art using a recursive algorithm for rectangle splitting. The number of rectangles can be anywhere from 32 to 16384. There are several different strategies for splitting, each one producing distinctive results. The background can be dark or light. Color palettes are generated programmatically in eight different ways (e.g. monochromatic, complementary, analogous, etc.). Textures and effects are also generated programmatically using Perlin noise and pixel manipulation. To add dynamics, there is a probability of having some uncertainty in drawing rectangles, dots, and lines.

metadata.name: square haze [86] #80
metadata.description:
Finally it is! Another one piece from square haze collection. This time it is generative fxhash item that represents aesthetics compilation found during previous pieces research on hic et nunc with some improvements discovered during fxhash adaptation. There are some features that controls generated token appearance:
- squareMode: different settings that determine algorithms used to create piece
- colorTheme: one of the best color palettes from the internet
- colorPicker: function used to select color schemes for grid mode
- grid: amount of splits in master square
- colorShift: step that determines how colors iterated in sub-squares (doesn't affect black and white squares)
- padding: yes
- bgIndex: sometimes it adds some vibe to the whole image
- isSiblings: probably the most awful part of the internal that looks great
- law: as it is normal or uniform, the hash will choose
- noiseChance: probability of new created square to became noisy one
- patternChance: the same as noise but with patttterns
- spread: something like dispersion for normal distribution I suppose
- border: minimal distance between squares
- minSize: minimal square size
- roundness: oh, this was accidental and fun, so it is included

There will be more.
Probably #87, #88, #89, #90 and #91
No ETA, no promises, don't know what differences will bring the future, but believing in the best.

27 May 2022 // NEURAL HAZE

metadata.name: Shift #233
metadata.description:
A generative algorithm honing the power of vertical displacement.

How simple may a generative algorithm be while simultaneously staying diverse enough for each art piece to be truly unique? Shift is the result of an exploration into this space, basing its existence on two principles — dissection and vertical shifting. Each variable in this art engine has been meticulously weighted, giving rise to high diversity and the possibility of epic combinations. 

Shift is a series of 888 unique pieces.

############

Display resolution is 1000x1400. Press ’s’ (in live mode) to generate a 6000x8400 hi-res image. This may take a while to generate depending on your hardware.

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2022

metadata.name: Miniscapes #280
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: Rhythms #234
metadata.description:
"Routines, patterns, cadence.
Events, turns, chaos.
Predictable lives,
split-second dramas."

This project is inspired by the delicate balance between daily habits and life-turning points.
There's structure in the flow. There's awe in the silence.

"Rhythms" invites you to reflect on the beautiful complexity that fills our vital experience, on the millions of tiny details that bring texture to our journey causing balance or disruption.

-

metadata.name: Bamboo #74
metadata.description:
During my childhood we had a small patch of bamboo in our backyard. 
I fondly remember playing with the hollow sticks but also cutting myself on the fibrous leaves.
"Bamboo" aims to capture the adventures I would envision while looking at that small jungle in my garden.

Inspiration was drawn from pointillism, botanical illustration and naive art.

The piece is purely generative, in the sense of painting the picture with code via p5js points and shapes, no assets are used.

Generative parameters include density of elements, parameters of elements and color. 

Thank you so much for collecting!

's' to capture a 6400 x 6400 png with border

'b' to capture a 6400 x 6400 png without border

metadata.name: Unsolicited abstraction of modern times #66
metadata.description:
This piece is an abstraction and a reflection on the last era, on all that we have built and become. Are we proud of it or has it just been the result of iterating through the days? Since the technology boom, we have experienced great improvements, but perhaps also massive ...mistakes?

metadata.name: Herbarium #249
metadata.description:
"Herbarium" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022

Occasionally, I stumble upon vintage scientific illustrations on various topics, exotically looking charts and graphs, alternative layouts for the periodic tables or psychological research diagrams, elaborate illustrations of botany and zoology, minerals, and natural and sometimes unnatural phenomena. Most of those illustrations are part of the "art and science" practices from the 18th and 19th centuries. At the core of those practices were observation and interpretation, unraveling complexity through visualizing abstract ideas or finding a creative approach for understanding previously incomprehensible forms. 

I'm an admirer of two female pioneers in the field. Maria Sibylla Merian created, with immense dedication, a book with intricate illustrations of plants and insects, later praised by scientists. On the other hand, Anna Atkins published a book with beautiful botanical cyanotypes, considered the first book with photographic images. These topics are the visual inspiration for pieces presented at ArtBasel HK. 

My mathematical background makes me naturally attracted to graphs, converting numbers to curves, and everything schematically displayed. Also, combining scientific symbols and illustrations with imaginary data inspires the spectator to find meaning in unrelated or random things or provokes latent skepticism towards assumed concepts of truth, reality, and knowledge.

metadata.name: Antiflow #509
metadata.description:
"Opposites are not contradictory but complementary." - Niels Bohr

The concept of yin and yang is an ancient philosophy about how opposing forces are not only complementary but actually give rise to each other. This idea reverberates through nature, art, and life itself. Now it is at the heart of modern physics. Perhaps this is a fundamental law of nature baked into the very fabric of existence.

Antiflow is an exploration of how balanced complexity can arise from chaos by harnessing the dynamic interplay of opposing forces. To that end we were inspired to create this wildly unique set by mixing modern physics concepts with abstract expressionism and retro 3D primitives.

The aspect ratio is 3:2 to facilitate poster size prints and device wallpapers. Results are presented without borders, noise, or other effects to allow for maximum detail. Feel free to rotate in whatever direction you choose for the best display.

Press "S" to save at a higher definition.

metadata.name: ‘Low-Res’ poems #5
metadata.description:
‘Low-Res’ poems is a collection as a high-tech alternative search. It was made with two free small, lightweight softwares like kidpix.app and magicavoxel, using the @PureSpider template to create iterations. This collection  is produced from technological limitations, a socioeconomic condition implies a determined political position and this is reflected on the access to technology, mainly the access to hardware.
As an artist, not having access to specialized high-tech hardware and software made my workflow, or the way I approach art, different, putting me in a place where I had to open myself and embrace low-poly or low-res alternatives to continue making art.

‘Low-Res’ has 50 MagicaVoxel models in 3D and 6 backgrounds made in kidpix.app, in each piece, the features combinations build corny poems, which give each piece an unique spirit and name. These poems work as a continuation of the Digital Collage collection.

High res tech has often been a vector of cultural hegemony over the global south, especially in terms of access to the tech- Sabatobox @sabatobox

metadata.name: Dencity #994
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ❤️, code and p5js.
